    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1957-06-05T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1957-06-05T00:00:00-05:00" n="446"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d446">
                <head>446. Memorandum of a Conversation, Department of State, Washington, June 5,
                        1957<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d446fn1">Source: Department of State,
                        Central Files, 751J.00/6–557. Confidential. Drafted by <persName
                            corresp="#p_ECB1">Elbrick</persName>. The following marginal note by
                            <persName corresp="#p_MWB1">Macomber</persName> appears on the source
                        text: “OK, WM”.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" type="conversation-or-meeting-date"
                            when="1957-06-05">
                            <hi rend="italic">June 5, 1957</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Laos</item>
                </list>
                <list type="participants">
                    <head>PARTICIPANTS</head>
                    <item>The Secretary</item>
                    <item>Ambassador <persName>Alphand</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>Mr. <persName>Charles Lucet</persName>, Minister, French Embassy</item>
                    <item>
                        <persName corresp="#p_ECB1">C. Burke Elbrick</persName>, <gloss
                            target="#t_EUR1">EUR</gloss>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <p>Ambassador Alphand said that the French Government is very worried about the
                    situation in Laos and referred to the fact that no Cabinet now existed in the
                    country. The Laotian Ambassador in Paris had made a démarche, to the French
                    Government in asking that the latter continue its economic and financial aid to
                    Laos. The French Government is prepared to do this and hopes that the United
                    States will also continue its aid. The Secretary said that he was not acquainted
                    with the most recent developments in Laos but he understood that no Government
                    had yet been created. He said that we would make a note of the French
                    Government’s request.</p>
            </div>
